# %ECSV 1.0
# ---
# datatype:
# - {name: wavelength, unit: nm, datatype: float64, description: Wavelength}
# - {name: differential photon rate, unit: 1e+09 / (nm s sr m2), datatype: float64, description: Differential photon rate}
# meta: !!omap
# - {Name: nsb_reference_spectrum}
# - {File: /workdir/external/simtools/tests/resources/model_parameters/Benn_LaPalma_sky_converted.ecsv}
# - {'Description:': NSB spectrum}
# - {context_from_sim_telarray: "Nightsky spectrum from Benn & Ellison (astro-ph/9909153 actually), in original units and converted\n\
#     to photons per wavelength interval, time, area, and solid angle.\n\nConversion factor from column two [microJy/(arcsec)^2] to column\
#     \ 3 [10^9 ph. / (nm s m^2 sr)] is\n1e-6*1e-23*1e-7*1e4/(lambda*1e-9/6.6260696e-34)*(pi/180./3600.)**(-2)/1e9/1e9 = 642.09/lambda\n\
#     [micro][Jy->erg][erg->J][cm**-2->m**-2][1/(h*nu)/(d lambda/d nu)][arcsec**-2->sr**-1][1/m->1/nm][1/s->1/ns]\nwhere lambda is the\
#     \ value in column one [nm] and (h*nu)*(d lambda/d nu) = h * lambda, using\nh = 6.6260696e-34 J*s,\n1 Jy = 10^-23 erg s^-1 cm^-2\
#     \ Hz^-1,\n1 microJy = 1e-6 * 1e-23 erg / s / cm^2 / Hz = 1e-6 * 1e-23 * 1e-7 J / s * 1e4 / m^2 / Hz = 1e-32 J / (s m^2 Hz).\n\n\
#     See also notes at the end of this file for further units and other sources of NSB.\n\nLambda     fnu (original)     diff. photon\
#     \ rate\n[nm ]   [microJy/(arcsec)^2] [10^9 / (nm s m^2 sr)]\n\nResults from the conversion into other commonly used units:\nIn the\
#     \ wavelength range 300 to 650 nm we have:\n2.60862e+12 photons / m^2 / s / sr\nIn a pixel of diameter 4.100 cm at a mirror of 106.3\
#     \ m^2 area and 15.00 m focal length we get:\n1.79415e+09 photons per pixel / s (without any losses).\nIn the V band we have a mean\
#     \ flux of 9.98773 microJansky/(arc sec)^2,\ncorresponding to magn. 21.40 / (arc sec)^2.\n\nFor comparison, NSB measurements at the\
#     \ La Palma HEGRA/MAGIC site are:\nMirzoyan & Lorenz (1994): (1.75+-0.4) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr) in 300-600 nm range.\nPreuss\
#     \ et al. (2002): (2.60+-0.35) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr) in 300-650 nm range\nfor Alt > 60 deg, |b| > 20 deg., no stars brighter\
#     \ than mag. 6.\nScaling the Mirzoyan & Lorenz measurement to the 300-650 nm range of the Preuss et al.\nmeasurement, using the B&E\
#     \ spectral shape, would be (2.41+-0.55) * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr)\nand the weighted average of the two would be (2.55+-0.30)\
#     \ * 10^{12} photons/(m^2 s sr),\nconsistent with the spectrum as in this file.\n\nWhile the astro-ph/9909153 paper describes the\
#     \ spectrum just as \"typical spectrum\",\nthe \"Technical Note 115\", apparently showing the same spectrum, describes it\nas taken\
#     \ in March 1991. That would be near solar maximum and the 1990-1992\naverage V band sky brightness on La Palma in Table 1 of TN115\
#     \ of magn. 21.5 / (arc sec)^2\nis consistent with the 21.40 derived above and with solar maximum expectations.\n\nAmong the other\
#     \ non-SI units are those for the luminance, like the Lambert (\"la\"),\nor Stilb (\"sb\"), related to the SI unit for luminous intensity\
#     \ Candela (\"cd\"):\n1 la = (1/pi) sb = (10^4/pi) cd/m^2.\n1 Candela is the luminous intensity of a monochromatic light source of\n\
#     540e12 Hertz frequency (i.e.555 nm) emitting a radiant intensity of 1/683 Watt / steradian.\nFor other wavelengths the sensitivity\
#     \ curve of the human eye for bright light is applied.\nThus better avoided and not really applicable for Cherenkov light background.\n\
#     \nA V band sky brightness of 22.0 mag within 1 (arc sec)^2,\nabout the darkest sky ever observed in zenith for clear sky,\ncorresponds\
#     \ to f_nu of 5.77 microJy/(arc sec)^2 near 550 nm or\n8.10e9 photons/(nm s m^2 sr). According to darksky.org information sheet #99\n\
#     it corresponds to a luminance of 2e-4 cd/m^2 or 54 nanoLamberts\n(note: direct conversion at 550 nm - at the peak of the human eye\
#     \ efficacy -\nwould result in about 84 nanoLamberts; the efficacy curve really matters).\nB&E TN115 quote a V band brightness of\
#     \ 21.9 mag for high elevation,\nhigh galactic latitude, high ecliptic latitude and near solar minimum,\nwith typical increase of\
#     \ 0.4 mag at solar maximum, 0.4 mag at low ecliptic\nlatitude, 0.25 mag at airmass 1.5 (zenith angle 48 deg.), and < 0.1 mag\nchange\
#     \ during the night.\n\nFor any conversion to astronomical magnitude units, keep in mind that\n1 Jy = 10^-23 erg sec^-1 cm^-2 Hz^-1,\n\
#     resulting in the transformation\n1 Jy = 1.51e7 photons sec^-1 m^-2 (dlambda/lambda)^-1\n\nThe most physical magnitude system is\
#     \ the AB system, with\nm(AB) = -2.5 log10(f_nu) - 48.60, with f_nu in erg/(s cm^2 Hz)\nor approximately\nm(AB) = -2.5 log10(f_nu\
#     \ / 3610 Jy).\nThe Johnson system has the following fluxes for magnitude zero:\nFilt. lambda  dlambda   mag 0\nname   [nm]   FWHM[nm]\
#     \   [Jy]\nU \t 360\t 150 \t1810\nB \t 440\t 220 \t4260\nV \t 550 \t 160\t3640\nR \t 640\t 230\t3080\nI \t 790\t 190\t2550\n\nTransformations\
#     \ between AB and Johnson magnitudes:\nB\t=   B(AB) + 0.163\nV\t=   V(AB) + 0.044\nR\t=   R(AB) - 0.055\nI\t=   I(AB) - 0.309\n\n\
#     A conversion between V magnitudes per square arc seconds (ms2) and\nnanoLamberts (nL) is: nL = 34.08 exp(20.7233 - 0.92104 ms2)\n\
#     [Krisciunas and Schaefer, PASP 103 (1991), 1033.]\nThe S10 unit (one mag 10 star per square degree) is 0.263 nL.\nAlso from Krisciunas\
#     \ and Schaefer is the sky brightness b [nL] as a\nfunction of zenith angle:\nb(z) = b(0) * 10^(-0.4*k*(X-1)) where X=(1-0.96*sin^2(z))^(-0.5)\n\
#     and k is the extinction coefficient in magnitudes per air mass X.\nThey give the following set of equations for the sky brightness\
#     \ due\nto moon light at separations above 10 degrees:\nI = 10^(-0.4*(3.84 + 0.026*abs(alpha) + 4e-9*alpha^4 - o))\nf(rho) = 10^5.36\
#     \ * (1.06+(cos(rho))^2) + 10^(6.15-rho/40)\nX(z) = (1 - 0.96*(sin(z))^2)^(-0.5)\nbm = f(rho) * I * 10^(-0.4*k*X(zm)) * (1-10^(-0.4*k*X(z)))\n\
#     with lunar phase angle: alpha [deg], moon/sky separation: rho, extinction\ncoefficient: k, zenith angle of the moon: zm, zenith\
#     \ angle of the\nsky position: z. This is ignoring the \"opposition effect\" where the\nmoon can be up to 35% brighter (for |alpha|\
#     \ < 7 deg), i.e. o=0.\nTo include this effect use something like o(alpha)=0.32*exp(-0.5*(alpha/5 deg)^2).\nResulting change in V-band\
#     \ sky brightness (no moon: b):\nDelta V = -2.5*log10((bm + b(z))/b(z))\n\nThe following are NSB brightess values for different moon\
#     \ phases\n(data from CTIO (A.R. Walker 1987), via wikipedia or from ESO):\nLunar Age \tU \tB \tV \tR \tI      z\n(days)\n0     22.0\
#     \    22.7    21.8    20.9    19.9    18.8\n3     21.5    22.4    21.7    20.8    19.9    18.8\n7     19.9    21.6    21.4    20.6\
#     \    19.7    18.6\n10     18.5    20.7    20.7    20.3    19.5    18.3\n14     17.0    19.5    20.0    19.9    19.2    18.1\nwith\
#     \ the values in the z filter band coming from\nhttp://www.eso.org/observing/etc/doc/helpfors.html#atmosphere .\n(Note that the spectrum\
#     \ of moon light is similar to the solar spectrum).\n\nA similar table for La Palma (http://www.tng.iac.es/info/la_palma_sky.html)\n\
#     Days from new moon\nU       B       V       R       I       z Gunn\n0     22.5    22.8    21.8    20.9    19.7    19.3\n3     22.3\
#     \    22.5    21.6    20.8    19.6    19.2\n7     21.4    21.4    20.7    20.2    19.1    18.7\n10     20.4    20.3    19.6    19.2\
#     \    18.2    17.8\n14     19.3    19.1    18.5    18.2    17.3    16.9\n\nBe aware that the two tables differ substantially in spectral\
#     \ behaviour\n(for CTIO differences in R and I are much smaller than at short\nwavelengths; for La Palma this is not the case).\n\
#     \nThe Benn & Ellison spectral data should be valid far from the galactic plane,\nalso from the ecliptic (little zodiacal light,\
#     \ which also has\na different spectrum), apparently near solar maximum (not explicit\nin the paper but indicated in TN115), no moon,\
#     \ _between_ stars\nbrighter than V=20 mag, corresponding (as reported by B&E TN 115 as 1990-1992 average)\nto values of B=22.5 mag/(arc\
#     \ sec)^2, V=21.5 mag/(arc sec)^2.\nNote that this is consistent with the value V=21.4 derived from the spectrum.\n\nCloser to the\
#     \ galactic plane, more and more star light gets included in\nthe NSB seen by a Cherenkov telescope, with a mixture of stellar spectra.\n\
#     \nZodiacal light as a function of ecliptic coordinates\nbased on Leinert, in units of 10-8 W m^-2 sr^-1 micrometer^-1 m-^1 (????)\
#     \ at a wavelength of 500 nm\n\"The scale factor to convert these units into photons cm^-2 s^-1 sr-^1 A^-1 is 252 at 5000 A; ie,\n\
#     the numbers in the table have to be multiplied by 252.\"\n(source: http://tauvex.iiap.res.in/tauwiki/index.php/Zodiacal_Light)\n\
#     For photons / (nm m^2 s sr) the conversion factor is then 2.52e7. Thus even at the poles\nof the ecliptic about a quarter of a V=22\
#     \ mag/(arc sec)^2 sky is still zodiacal light.\n\nbeta |   0       5       10      15      20      25      30      45      60  \
#     \    75      90 <- hel. long.\n---- |   --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --      --\n0  \
#     \  |                           3140    1610    985     640     275     150     100     77\n5    |                           2940\
#     \    1540    945     625     271     150     100     77\n10   |                   4740    2470    1370    865     590     264  \
#     \   148     100     77\n15   |   11500   6780    3440    1860    1110    755     525     251     146     100     77\n20   |   6400\
#     \    4480    2410    1410    910     635     454     237     141     99      77\n25   |   3840    2830    1730    1100    749  \
#     \   545     410     223     136     97      77\n30   |   2480    1870    1220    845     615     467     365     207     131   \
#     \  95      77\n35   |   1650    1270    910     680     510     397     320     193     125     93      77\n40   |   1180    940\
#     \     700     530     416     338     282     179     120     92      77\n45   |   910     730     555     442     356     292 \
#     \    250     166     116     90      77\n60   |   505     442     352     292     243     209     183     134     104     86   \
#     \   77\n75   |   338     317     269     227     196     172     151     116     93      82      77\n90   |   259     251     225\
#     \     193     166     147     132     104     86      79      77\n105  |   212     210     197     170     150     133     119 \
#     \    96      82      77      77\n120  |   188     186     177     154     138     125     113     90      77      74      77\n135\
#     \  |   179     178     166     147     134     122     110     90      77      73      77\n150  |   179     178     165     148\
#     \     137     127     116     96      79      72      77\n165  |   196     192     179     165     151     141     131     104 \
#     \    82      72      77\n180  |   230     212     195     178     163     148     134     105     83      72      77\nwith a spectrum\
#     \ derived from the solar spectrum but - because of small scattering\nparticles - expected to have somewhat higher relative intensity\
#     \ in the blue (?)\n\nAnd then there are all the stars brighter than V=20 in addition ..."}
